    "storage": {
      "value": "<p>The meteorological wind direction is the direction from which the wind is blowing.</p><p><ac:image ac:thumbnail=\"true\" ac:height=\"250\"><ri:attachment ri:filename=\"wind-speed.png\" /></ac:image></p><p>Wind direction increases clockwise such that a northerly wind is 0&deg;, an easterly wind is 90&deg;, a southerly wind is 180&deg;, and a westerly wind is 270&deg;. <br />Because trigonometry uses a polar coordinate system in which 0&deg; is along the x axis, the meteorological angle definition can wreak havoc on typical angle calculations. <br />Fortunately, it is still easy to compute the wind components, u and v, given the meteorological wind angle. Let &Phi; be the meteorological wind direction angle, then the following equations can be applied:</p><p><ac:image ac:align=\"left\" ac:thumbnail=\"true\" ac:height=\"134\"><ri:attachment ri:filename=\"wind-formula.png\" /></ac:image></p><p><br /></p><p><br /></p><p><br /></p><p><br /></p><p><br /></p><p>Note that &Phi; must be in radians. If &Phi; is in degrees, multiply the angle by &pi;/180 before using the trig function.</p><p>It is also possible to compute &Phi; from u and v using the atan2 function. The atan2 arguments vary by type of software. <br /><br />On a spreadsheet, use the following equation to get an answer in degrees:</p><p><ac:image ac:thumbnail=\"true\" ac:height=\"58\"><ri:attachment ri:filename=\"wind-direction.png\" /></ac:image></p><h2>Related articles</h2><p><ac:placeholder>Related articles appear here based on the labels you select. Click to edit the macro and add or change labels.</ac:placeholder></p><p><ac:structured-macro ac:name=\"contentbylabel\" ac:schema-version=\"3\" ac:macro-id=\"e2bdb250-f4fe-4d8e-becf-ba0277ea3753\"><ac:parameter ac:name=\"showLabels\">false</ac:parameter><ac:parameter ac:name=\"max\">5</ac:parameter><ac:parameter ac:name=\"spaces\">CKB</ac:parameter><ac:parameter ac:name=\"showSpace\">false</ac:parameter><ac:parameter ac:name=\"sort\">modified</